<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-09-22T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-09-22T12:00:00-05:00" n="357" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d357">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">811.113 Senate Investigation/60:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Argentina</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Weddell</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Buenos Aires</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-09-22T13:00:00-04:00">September
                                    22, 1934—1 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received September 23—10:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>166. Further supplementing my 163, September 20, 6 p.m., the Minister for
                            Foreign Affairs today told me that he considered the matter as now
                            ended; that within a fortnight local public opinion would have cooled
                            down and the matter be forgotten.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Weddell</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>